"Sussex, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1100–1170":"1100–1170","1095–1169":"1095–1169","1121–Male":"1121–Afdød","1127–Male":"1127–Afdød","1130–1176":"1130–1176","1130–1190":"1130–1190","1140–1198":"1140–1198","1190":"1190","about 1140":"omkring 1140","1121":"1121","1198":"1198","1176":"1176","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","1095":"1095","1170":"1170","1106":"1106","1127":"1127","1104":"1104","1169":"1169","about 1127":"omkring 1127","1100":"1100","1122":"1122","about 1130":"omkring 1130","Newtimber, Sussex":"Newtimber, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Coxford, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Quesnay, Estrées la Campagne, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Estrées-la-Campagne, Calvados, Normandie, Frankrig","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Skotland","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1100–1170":"1100–1170","1095–1169":"1095–1169","1121–Male":"1121–Overleden","1127–Male":"1127–Overleden","1130–1176":"1130–1176","1130–1190":"1130–1190","1140–1198":"1140–1198","1190":"1190","about 1140":"circa 1140","1121":"1121","1198":"1198","1176":"1176","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","1095":"1095","1170":"1170","1106":"1106","1127":"1127","1104":"1104","1169":"1169","about 1127":"circa 1127","1100":"1100","1122":"1122","about 1130":"circa 1130","Newtimber, Sussex":"Newtimber, Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Coxford, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Quesnay, Estrées la Campagne, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Estrées-la-Campagne, Calvados, Normandie, Frankrijk","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Schotland","Sussex, England":"Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1100–1170":"1100–1170","1095–1169":"1095–1169","1121–Male":"1121–Deceased","1127–Male":"1127–Deceased","1130–1176":"1130–1176","1130–1190":"1130–1190","1140–1198":"1140–1198","1190":"1190","about 1140":"about 1140","1121":"1121","1198":"1198","1176":"1176","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","1095":"1095","1170":"1170","1106":"1106","1127":"1127","1104":"1104","1169":"1169","about 1127":"about 1127","1100":"1100","1122":"1122","about 1130":"about 1130","Newtimber, Sussex":"Newtimber, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Coxford, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Quesnay, Estrées la Campagne, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Estrées-la-Campagne, Calvados, Normandy, France","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Dominique.","English: from the female personal name <i>Elizabeth</i>, which owed its popularity in medieval Europe to the fact that it was borne by John the Baptist's mother. The original form of the name was Hebrew <i>Elisheva</i> ‘my God (is my) oath’ and it appears thus in Exodus 6:23 as the name of Aaron's wife. By New Testament times the second element had been altered to Hebrew <i>shabat</i> ‘rest, Sabbath’. The personal name became even more popular after the canonization of Elisabeth, Duchess of Thuringia around 1230. See also   Isabel  .","West Indian (Dutch Caribbean): from the female personal name <i>Elizabeth</i> (see 1 above). It is one of the surnames (compare   Martina  ) that reflect the partially mother-oriented name culture of the formerly enslaved people in the West Indies."],"variants":[{"name":"Behlen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Fritz, Kurt.","German: metronymic from <i>Abele</i> or <i>Hebele</i>, pet forms ofthe female personal name <i>Elisabeth</i> (see   Elizabeth  ), thesuffix <i>-n</i> being the (weak) genitive ending; thus ‘(husband orson) of <i>Bele</i>’."]},{"name":"Beilke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Kurt, Gerhard, Helmuth, Otto.","German:","from a pet form of <i>Beile</i>, itself a pet form of <i>Elisabeth</i> (see   Elizabeth  )."]},{"name":"Isabel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Alfonso, Alvarado, Augusto, Belia, Josefina, Juan, Manuel, Mario, Romero, Santa.","French, Spanish, Portuguese, and English (of French origin): from the Old French female personal name <i>Isabel</i>, which is first recorded in late 11th-century Paris and Maine (France). It was an alternative form of   Elizabeth  , Old French <i>Elisabet</i>, which had a shortened pet form <i>Isabet</i>. <i>Isabel</i> appears to have originated as a variant of <i>Isabet</i>, in which the suffix <i>-el</i> was substituted for <i>-et</i> through re-interpretation of <i>-et</i> as a hypocoristic diminutive. The resultant <i>-bel</i> was early associated with Old French <i>bel</i> ‘fair, beautiful’, as is evident in the French variant <i>Isabeau</i>. From France the name was taken to England, where it achieved considerable popularity in the late medieval period as an independent personal name alongside its rarer doublet <i>Elizabeth</i>. In the form <i>Isabel</i> it also appears in Spain and Portugal, while in Italy it took the form   Isabella  . The French surnames <i>Isabel</i> and   Isabelle   are particularly associated with Normandy.","History: Michel Isabel from Reux in Calvados, France, married Marie Jobidon in Château-Richer, QC, in 1673."]},{"name":"Elsenpeter","meanings":["German: variant of <b>Elspeter</b>, an extinct metronymic from a vernacular form of the personal name <i>Elisabeth</i> (see   Elizabeth  ) or a habitational name for someone from Elsbethen near Salzburg, Austria. The surname <i>Elsenpeter</i> is very rare in Germany."]},{"name":"Elser","meanings":["German: metronymic from the personal name <i>Else</i>, a short form of <i>Elisabeth</i> (see   Elizabeth  ).","North German: topographic name for someone who lived near alders, from Low German <i>else</i> ‘alder’.","North German: habitational name for someone from any of the places called Elsen in Rhineland and Westphalia."]},{"name":"Delisa","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Dino, Gino, Romeo.","Italian (<b>De Lisa</b> or <b>D'Elisa</b>): metronymic, with the preposition <i>d(e)</i> ‘of’, from the female personal names <i>Lisa</i> or <i>Elisa</i>, short forms of <i>Elisabetta</i>, an equivalent of   Elizabeth  ."]},{"name":"Betten","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Claus, Dieter, Manfred.","Dutch and North German: metronymic from the personal name <i>Bette</i>, a shortened form of <i>Elisabeth</i> (see   Elizabeth  ), or a patronymic from <i>Bet</i>, a pet form of   Berthold   (see   Beth  )."]},{"name":"Elsner","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Wolfgang, Alfons, Dieter, Egon, Ernst, Erwin, Eward, Hans, Heinz, Lutz, Manfred.","German:","northern topographic name for someone who lived near alders, from Low German <i>else</i> ‘alder’. It may also be a habitational name for someone from a place called with this word. In Silesia it has the same meaning, but is of ultimate Slavic origin. This surname is also found elsewhere in central Europe, e.g. in Czechia and Slovenia, where it may (also) be a translation into German of corresponding Slavic surnames."]},{"name":"Elsen","meanings":["German, Flemish, and Dutch: metronymic from a short form of the female personal name <i>Elisabeth</i> (see   Elizabeth  ).","German; Dutch (also <b>Van Elsen</b>): habitational name from a place so named in North Rhine-Westphalia.","Flemish and Dutch (also <b>Van Elsen</b>): habitational name for someone from any of various places called Elzen, for example in North Brabant in the Netherlands and in the provinces of Brabant and Liège in Belgium."]},{"name":"Elsbernd","meanings":["German: metronymic name meaning ‘Bernd, son of Els’, <i>Els</i> here a short form of the personal name <i>Elisabeth</i> (see   Elizabeth  )."]}]},{"name":"Sybil","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Sybilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sibilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sybille","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Sybil</b> ."]},{"name":"Sibella","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":6,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Sybil Elizabeth was born in 1100, in Sussex, England, United Kingdom. She married John de Caisneto Cheyne in 1122, in Sussex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1170, in Perthshire, Scotland, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1100–1170":"1100–1170","1095–1169":"1095–1169","1121–Male":"1121–Surnud","1127–Male":"1127–Surnud","1130–1176":"1130–1176","1130–1190":"1130–1190","1140–1198":"1140–1198","1190":"1190","about 1140":"umbes 1140","1121":"1121","1198":"1198","1176":"1176","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","1095":"1095","1170":"1170","1106":"1106","1127":"1127","1104":"1104","1169":"1169","about 1127":"umbes 1127","1100":"1100","1122":"1122","about 1130":"umbes 1130","Newtimber, Sussex":"Newtimber, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Coxford, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Quesnay, Estrées la Campagne, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Estrées-la-Campagne, Calvados, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","Sussex, England":"Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1100–1170":"1100–1170","1095–1169":"1095–1169","1121–Male":"1121–Kuollut","1127–Male":"1127–Kuollut","1130–1176":"1130–1176","1130–1190":"1130–1190","1140–1198":"1140–1198","1190":"1190","about 1140":"noin 1140","1121":"1121","1198":"1198","1176":"1176","1130":"1130",